This was a deliberate change to the internal `MockMonitor` class. We changed it in  https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/pull/14118 to say it supports all features (other than `"outputValues"`). This means the mock monitor now says it supports the `"aliasSpecs"` feature, which tells SDKs to stop computing aliases (sent via `request.aliasURNs`) and instead to send just the [alias "specs"](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/blob/6e94043cfb37ff54832c09b0d69d76ddf1c75f94/proto/pulumi/alias.proto#L21-L38) (sent via `request.aliases`). When alias specs are sent, the engine will compute the alias URNs and combination of aliases for parents, etc. This aligns with the behavior of real usage, as SDKs are no longer computing aliases when running with current releases of the CLI.

[`MockMonitor`](https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/blob/6e94043cfb37ff54832c09b0d69d76ddf1c75f94/sdk/python/lib/pulumi/runtime/mocks.py#L138) isn't intended to be used directly by users&mdash;it's an internal implementation detail of the mocking capability that isn't "exported" from the `runtime` subpackage. It probably should have been named `_MockMonitor` to make this more clear. But certainly understand why it's being used to get at some of this extra data to validate in tests.

I've opened https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/issues/14421 to track adding an officially supported way to expose such additional data needed for unit tests, which won't be affected by changes to internals like this.

In the meantime, since you're already subclassing `MockMonitor`, you can easily go back to the previous behavior by overriding the `SupportsFeature` method and returning `"hasSupport": False` when `request.id == "aliasSpecs"`, e.g. something like:

```python
class MyMockMonitor(MockMonitor):
    def SupportsFeature(self, request):
        # Disable aliasSpecs so we continue to get aliases populated in request.aliasURNs
        # in RegisterResource.
        if request.id == "aliasSpecs":
            return type("SupportsFeatureResponse", (object,), {"hasSupport": False})

        return super().SupportsFeature(request)
```

This will make the SDK go back to computing aliases and sending them as `request.aliasURNs` in `RegisterResource`.
